    # [Scene: Repaired Pier | Sunset]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, swelling strings; a low hopeful hum builds]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant pumps settling into a steadier rhythm; gulls calling; the soft slap of water against pilings]
    "You lean your weight into the rail and let the sea-dozen breaths of the town roll through you — each one a ledger of what was lost and what was kept. Whether it was the occupation"
    "at Voss's site that dragged national attention into our mud or Avi's late-night signatures that forced legal wetlands onto the maps, the essential truth is the same: the town pushed back and the push took."
    "The air smells of salt, wet wood, and loam — not all the same breath, layered like a promise. Your bronze compass pendant is warm against your sternum, its metal heartbeat syncing with the pumps' slower"
    "thrum. Around you, people laugh with salt-cracked voices; they curse with relief; they pass a battered wheelbarrow across new boards, palms smudged with peat."
    "You feel the climb beneath your feet: small, steady steps that began in the laboratory and ended here at the edge of water and work."
    "Jonah crosses the span toward you, film camera bouncing against his chest. He moves with that easy gait he always has, the bright patches on his jacket catching the sun. Up close, his amber eyes crinkle;"
    "he breathes in the smell of the garden crates and smiles like someone who has found a pocket of peace."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Look at this mess we made into something that might actually hold water the next time the sky decides to be arson."
    show mara_solano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_solano "Mess is generous. We made a plan, then the sea made the rest of the plan for us."

    jonah_reyes "You always sound like you designed the weather to be dramatic. Good PR, honestly."
    "You laugh — it comes out thin, then thickens into something steadier."

    mara_solano "I meant it. We have grants coming. Legal covenants. The co-op finally has a line item for paid labor. People are signing up to plant marsh terrace after terrace. Rosa and Mateo are already organizing shifts."

    jonah_reyes "And Elena? Her spokespeople—"
    "You glance toward the Spire across the reclaimed district. A mirrored rectangle of glass reflects the sunset like a wound bandaged with light. You don't need to name the woman who tried to fence the shoreline in concrete; her campaign faltered the way brittle things do in weather."

    mara_solano "Her PR took a hit. National outlets started asking questions about her models. Claire's analysis made the numbers look... less unassailable."
    "Jonah's smile fades for a beat — not in accusation, but in the way people soften when they remember what was almost lost."

    jonah_reyes "You were right to push. Even when I couldn’t see all the angles, you kept finding them."

    mara_solano "I was terrified, Jonah. Every move felt like weighing people's houses against their lives. I still am."
    "Jonah reaches out and takes one of your fingers between his thumb and forefinger, his hand grubby at the nails, the skin nicked where rope burned had been a constant during the occupation and the heavy lifting that followed."

    jonah_reyes "Then let fear be useful. Let it point you. I'm not asking you to be fearless — I'm asking you to be in this with me."
    "You hold his gaze. There is history there: a thousand small salvations and the shape of a shared childhood, the awkwardness of being trusted with more than you asked for."

    mara_solano "I don't know how to be anything but responsible. I don't want my stubbornness to become someone else's debt."

    jonah_reyes "Then trade stubbornness for stubbornness together. I'm stubborn for the market, you for the marshes. Two stubborn people — probably illegal somewhere."
    "A laugh bubbles out of you. Around the pier, volunteers exchange stories about which house blocks will be prioritized and which ones will have to be elevated over time. The rooftop gardens of La Plaza flicker in the distance, lanterns twinkling as workers shift seedlings under the last light."

    menu:
        "Join Rosa and Mateo to inventory supplies now":
            "You shoulder a crate of coir rolls and feel the immediate, useful ache of labor. Rosa claps you on the back; Mateo grins like a man who remembers every tide. The work steadies your chest."
        "Walk the pier with Jonah and talk through the next grant report":
            "You and Jonah spread a soggy set of grant papers on a crate. He reads aloud, fingers tracing budgets like a hymn. Planning quiets your worry in a different way."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues with Jonah watching your face; life and choices continue regardless of which action you take."
    "Jonah watches your face during the choice, his expression open and unreadable in parts — gratitude, mischief, exhaustion — all layered. You realize you don't need everything to be cleanly sorted to keep going; you only need to keep choosing."

    mara_solano "There will be neighborhoods we can't save right away. We will lose some houses. We already have. That doesn't mean it's all for nothing."

    jonah_reyes "No. It means we learn where to dig deeper and where to build higher. And it means we do it in a way that doesn't step on the people who stayed."

    mara_solano "Do you ever think about leaving? About putting all this behind and starting fresh somewhere not constantly on the edge?"
    "Jonah's fingers trail along a plank, finding a notch he used to carve as a kid."

    jonah_reyes "Sometimes. But every time I imagine a place without the smell of the market or Pilar's hands or you rolling your eyes at my jokes, it just... doesn't feel like living. It feels like exile."
    "His honesty is simple and raw. You want to answer with the fullness of what you feel — loyalty braided with fear — but some of it clings to your ribcage where guilt sits like moss."
    "Aunt Pilar's voice calls softly from where she's directing two teenagers into a planting rotation. She moves like a lighthouse — small, steady, entirely present."
    show aunt_pilar at center:
        zoom 0.7

    aunt_pilar "Mara, Jonah — come up to La Plaza in ten. The rooftop needs the last of the salt-marsh plugs. Sit with me first if you're going to talk too much."

    mara_solano "You always know when we need to be put to work."

    aunt_pilar "Work feeds the soul, niña. Complaining feeds the storm."
    "You glance at Jonah. He cocks his head like someone sensing ceremony."

    jonah_reyes "Before we go up? I—"

    jonah_reyes "I made this when I was twelve."

    mara_solano "Jonah—"

    jonah_reyes "We have rubble and laws and seedlings. I have this. Do you want it?"
    "There's something about the way he waits that makes you want to crawl inside the small, bright place he has carved out of ordinary things."

    menu:
        "Let Jonah slip the ring on your finger":
            "You lift your hand. The seagrass slides over your knuckle; it fits imperfectly and perfectly. Jonah's grin spills into a laugh that sounds like repair."
        "Tell Jonah to keep it until things settle":
            "You take the ring and close your fingers over it, putting the choice into Jonah's palm. He nods, understanding settling across his features like sunlight. The ring is a promise still warm."

    # --- merge ---
    "Whether the ring is worn now or kept for later, the meaning remains; the scene continues with shared intent."
    "Jonah watches your action with an expression that is complex and tender — some things in him unreadable but not cold; gratitude and relief and the small tremor of someone who dares to hope."
    "You let the moment be what it is. Whether the ring rests now on your finger or sits in his hand, the meaning — the mutual binding to the place and to each other — is no less real."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Gardens of La Plaza | Dusk]
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mara_solano
    hide aunt_pilar

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Earth being tamped into planters; distant laughter; the occasional metallic creak of a repair being tested]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle acoustic guitar joins the strings; a warmth builds]
    "You climb the narrow path up to the rooftop with Jonah at your side. The gardens smell of citrus and wet soil — the smell of things that keep giving. People pass you a box of"
    "seedlings; a teenager hands you a trowel with a grin that looks shockingly like Aunt Pilar's."
    show mara_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_solano "We did an intake this morning. Mateo logged twenty households for priority planting and five for phased elevation work. Rosa has a spreadsheet that reads like a litany of stubborn hope."
    show jonah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Good spreadsheets. I shoot bad ones for my film column."
    "You both laugh. The sound hangs over the city like a little flag."
    "You sit on the edge of a planter and rest your palm on the wet dirt. Your fingers find a kernel of something — a bit of shell maybe, a memory. Claire's face flashes in your"
    "mind, the careful empathy she carried as she walked flooded streets with you, the way science became armor and compass rather than doctrine."
    "Mara Solano [Thinking]: We won a breathing space. It is enough to start. It is not everything, but it is not nothing. That's enough to teach the town how to keep fighting without burning out."
    "Jonah tucks a stray tendril of your hair behind your ear, and for a second you are thirteen again, trading secret snacks on a crumbling pier. Then you are here: older, salted, wiser in smaller, harder ways."

    jonah_reyes "We'll teach them to make the marshes sing back. We'll turn broken places into new edges for life, for work, for market stalls that aren't running on fear."

    mara_solano "And we'll keep watching. We build the terraces and we watch how the water comes. We adapt, not to erase the past, but to live with it — better."

    jonah_reyes "Promise?"
    "You meet his eyes. There are no theatrics — only the honest alignment of two stubborn people choosing to keep choosing each other and the town."

    mara_solano "Promise."
    hide mara_solano
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings swell into a warm chord; a soft wind sound carries the scent of loam down to the pier]
    "At the pier again, dusk settles fully. You look at the repaired boards underfoot and see the scars, the mismatched planks, the new bolts. Each imperfection is a record of labor and love. Volunteers wave from"
    "the breakwater, their silhouettes bright against the falling light. Grants and covenants have not healed everything, but they bought time and gave the town agency."
    "Mara Solano [Thinking]: This is not a conclusion; it is a beginning made of small, daily continuations. We have agreements and money and people willing to get their hands dirty, but the real work is the living that comes after the headlines fade. This is what you came back for."
    "Jonah squeezes your hand. His thumb rubs the back of your knuckle where salt has left a white star."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "You carried too much for too long. Let us carry it with you."
    "You look at him and finally allow the exhaustion to unravel into something quieter: a steady, cautious joy that feels like a tide receding only to reveal the ground beneath — ground you can walk on and seed."
    show mara_solano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_solano "We rebuild. We stay. We make new ground out of high water."

    jonah_reyes "We make it stubbornly beautiful."
    "Your compass pendant buzzes faintly in its old way; the noise is not data but metaphor now — a small mechanical pulse that keeps you pointed. You feel the climb in your ribs and the town's"
    "breath around your shoulders. There are losses; there will always be losses. But the cooperative has traction, legal protections exist that didn't yesterday, and people who watched from the windows of houses that survived come down"
    "to plant that first row by hand."
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mara_solano

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle swell resolves into a single, sustaining note that lingers]
    "You let the dusk settle. For the first time in a long time you allow yourself to imagine seasons: marshes growing, seedlings thickening, the market refusing to vanish. Jonah leans his head against your shoulder, and"
    "you rest your cheek against his crown as if you could anchor the whole small world between your bodies."
    "A volunteer calls out a joke from the breakwater. Someone starts to sing an old work song, and people pick it up, stitching the present into the town's long, ragged music."
    "You breathe. The pendant warms. The plans — Claire's vetted models, the co-op's ledger, the civic covenants — are not miracle cures. They are scaffolding. They are arms around a wounded place."
    "Mara Solano [Thinking]: Love did not make the sea stop. Love made us refuse to accept what the sea offered as inevitable."
    "A breeze lifts the edges of Jonah's jacket and carries with it the small, clean scent of new soil and the faint smell of frying from a market stall. Jonah's camera hangs quiet and soot-streaked; it has been witness and proof and memory."
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Ready to be boring adults who plant things in the mud?"
    "You laugh, and your laugh is full and near to tears."
    show mara_solano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_solano "Yeah. Let's be the most boring, stubborn adults in the world."
    "He lifts your hand and, with a slow tenderness, slips the seagrass ring onto your finger (or presses it into your palm and then settles it there between you — it matters less which, and more"
    "that it is done). The fit is imperfect, like the town: not seamless, but right in the way that counts."

    jonah_reyes "So we rebuild, Mara Solano. Together."

    mara_solano "Together."
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide mara_solano

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Final chord — warm, insistent, resolved]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The pumps click into a steady, softer cycle; the sea breathes]
    "You close your eyes for a single long breath and open them into a future that is not unscarred but is now possible. The town will not be the same — it will be reinvented at"
    "every high tide and every low — but you and Jonah and this stitched community will be there to shape the terms. Grants will have strings; covenants will need enforcement; storms will test every plan. You"
    "will fail sometimes. You will also, now and often, succeed."

    "Aunt Pilar squeezes your shoulder and gives you a look that says, without many words" "You kept your promise."
    "Mara Solano [Thinking]: The promise was never to save everything. It was to try, to keep trying, and to make the town's willers and keepers count in the plans that decide their fate."
    "The sun finally slips below the line. Lanterns glow higher. The pier creaks with life. You feel, for the first time in many tides, that hope is not naive; it is a practiced muscle."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
